

                      SEDIT v1.10 Technical Manual
                  Build Environment and Source Reference

                    ================================


    1.  OVERVIEW

    SEDIT is a modular full-screen editor for CP/M 2.2, written
    entirely in Intel 8080 assembly language.  It is assembled with
    Microsoft Macro-80 (M80) and linked with Microsoft Link-80 (L80).
    The source is organized into 12 separately assembled modules plus
    a shared include file.

    Total source: approximately 13,500 lines across all modules.
    Binary size: approximately 15 KB (SEDIT.COM).


    2.  SOURCE FILES

    2.1  Linked Modules (in link order)

    Module          Lines  Purpose
    -------         -----  -------
    SEDIT.MAC        ~860  Entry point, main loop, action dispatch,
                           TPA detection, buffer descriptor, dirty
                           flag management
    SESCREEN.MAC    ~1740  Terminal I/O, screen rendering (SCRDRAW,
                           SCREDCL), info bar, cursor positioning,
                           VT100 escape sequence output, SGR color
    SEKEY.MAC        ~610  Keyboard input, VT100 escape sequence
                           decoding, key type/action classification
    SEGAPBUF.MAC    ~3160  Gap buffer text engine: insert, delete,
                           cursor movement, line operations, word
                           movement, page up/down, line counting
    SEFILEIO.MAC    ~1340  File load (FIOPEN) and save (FISAVE),
                           FCB management, .BAK file handling,
                           overflow to virtual buffer (FIOVFL)
    SEMENU.MAC       ~850  ESC menu overlay, 9 menu options with
                           handlers, column mode toggle, about box
    SESEARCH.MAC     ~620  Find and find-next, case-insensitive
                           string search through gap buffer
    SEBLOCK.MAC      ~720  Block mark, copy, delete, paste with
                           2048-byte clipboard buffer
    SESYNTAX.MAC     ~860  Assembly syntax highlighting tokenizer,
                           keyword/register/directive tables
    SEKEYBND.MAC     ~500  Key binding initialization, SEDIT.KEY
                           file parser, default binding tables
    SEVIRTIO.MAC    ~1440  Virtual buffer I/O for files larger than
                           TPA: temp file management, VIGOTO merge-
                           split, three-phase save (VISAVALL)
    SEHELP.MAC       ~420  Help screen overlay, BMDATEND marker
                           (must be linked last)

    2.2  Include File

    SEDIT.INC              Shared equates: BDOS function numbers,
                           ASCII codes, screen layout constants,
                           buffer descriptor field offsets, key
                           action codes, conditional assembly flags

    2.3  Standalone Utilities (not linked into SEDIT.COM)

    GETWIDTH.MAC     ~250  Terminal width detection utility
    KEYCODE.MAC            Key code diagnostic tool

    2.4  Build Scripts and Tools

    CPMFMT.PY              Python preprocessor (see section 3)
    build-1.bat            Windows build script using cpmulator
    BUILD.SUB              CP/M native build script (for SUBMIT)


    3.  BUILD PROCESS

    3.1  Prerequisites

    To build on a modern system (Windows):
      - Python 3.x (for CPMFMT.PY)
      - cpmulator.exe (CP/M emulator for running M80/L80)
      - M80.COM (Microsoft Macro-80 assembler)
      - L80.COM (Microsoft Link-80 linker)

    To build natively on CP/M:
      - M80.COM and L80.COM on an accessible disk
      - SUBMIT.COM (for BUILD.SUB) or manual commands

    3.2  Step 1: Preprocessing with CPMFMT.PY

        python CPMFMT.PY SEDIT.MAC SESCREEN.MAC SEKEY.MAC ...

    Or to process all .MAC files:

        python CPMFMT.PY

    CPMFMT.PY performs three operations:

    a) INCLUDE expansion: Replaces any line containing
       "INCLUDE SEDIT.INC" with the literal contents of SEDIT.INC.
       This is necessary because M80 terminates input when it
       encounters the Ctrl-Z EOF marker in an included file.

    b) Line ending normalization: Converts all line endings to
       CR+LF (0DH 0AH) as required by CP/M text files.

    c) EOF marker: Appends a Ctrl-Z (1AH) byte at the end of the
       file.

    CPMFMT.PY is idempotent: after the first run, the INCLUDE
    directive has been replaced by inlined content, so subsequent
    runs only redo CR+LF normalization and EOF marking.

    IMPORTANT: CPMFMT.PY must be run after every edit to a .MAC
    file.  Failure to do so may cause M80 assembly errors or
    produce incorrect output.

    3.3  Step 2: Assembly

    Each module is assembled separately to produce a .REL
    (relocatable object) file:

        M80 =SEDIT
        M80 =SESCREEN
        M80 =SEKEY
        M80 =SEGAPBUF
        M80 =SEFILEIO
        M80 =SEMENU
        M80 =SESEARCH
        M80 =SEBLOCK
        M80 =SESYNTAX
        M80 =SEKEYBND
        M80 =SEVIRTIO
        M80 =SEHELP

    The "=filename" syntax tells M80 to read filename.MAC and
    produce filename.REL.

    3.4  Step 3: Linking

        L80 SEDIT,SESCREEN,SEKEY,SEGAPBUF,SEFILEIO,SEMENU,...
            SESEARCH,SEBLOCK,SESYNTAX,SEKEYBND,SEVIRTIO,...
            SEHELP,SEDIT/N/E

    The /N flag suppresses the symbol table listing.  The /E flag
    tells L80 to produce the .COM file and exit.  The last argument
    before /N/E is the output filename (SEDIT.COM).

    CRITICAL: SEHELP must be the LAST module in the link order.
    See section 5.3 for the reason.

    3.5  Quick Build (Windows)

    The build-1.bat script automates all three steps:

        build-1.bat

    It runs CPMFMT.PY, assembles all modules via cpmulator, links,
    cleans up .REL files, and copies the result to the disk image
    directory.

    3.6  Quick Build (CP/M native)

    Copy BUILD.SUB to the disk containing the source and tools:

        SUBMIT BUILD

    This runs all M80 and L80 commands in sequence.  Note that
    BUILD.SUB does not run CPMFMT.PY; source files must be
    preprocessed before transfer to CP/M media.


    4.  CONDITIONAL ASSEMBLY OPTIONS

    Two equates in SEDIT.INC control compile-time features.  Since
    CPMFMT.PY inlines SEDIT.INC into each .MAC file, these values
    are present in every module.  To change them, either:

    a) Edit SEDIT.INC and re-run CPMFMT.PY on all .MAC files
       (requires restoring the INCLUDE directive first), or

    b) Edit the inlined equates directly in each .MAC file that
       uses them (SESCREEN.MAC and SESYNTAX.MAC).

    4.1  COLOR

        COLOR   EQU   1        ; 1 = color, 0 = monochrome

    Controls whether SGR color escape sequences (foreground colors)
    are included in the binary.  Set to 0 for monochrome terminals
    that do not support ANSI color.  When COLOR=0, the color escape
    sequence strings (SGRMAG, SGRGRN, etc.) are omitted, saving
    space and avoiding garbled output on non-color terminals.

    Bold (SGR 1), dim (SGR 2), and reverse video (SGR 7) are always
    available regardless of the COLOR setting.

    4.2  SYNHI

        SYNHI   EQU   0        ; 0=none, 1=ASM, 2=C (future)

    Controls syntax highlighting at compile time:

      0  No syntax highlighting (smallest binary)
      1  8080/Z80 assembly language highlighting

    When SYNHI=0, the syntax tokenizer code in SESYNTAX.MAC and
    the highlighting rendering code in SESCREEN.MAC are excluded
    via conditional assembly (IF SYNHI ... ENDIF).

    Note: Syntax mode detection (SYNINIT) always runs regardless
    of the SYNHI setting; it sets BD_SYNMD based on file extension
    but the value is only acted upon if SYNHI is nonzero.


    5.  MEMORY LAYOUT

    5.1  CP/M Memory Map

        0000H-00FFH     CP/M page zero (warm boot, BDOS entry,
                        default FCB at 005CH, command tail at 0080H)
        0100H           Program load address (START entry point)
        0100H-xxxx      SEDIT code and data (DSEG + CSEG per module)
        BMDATEND        End of static code/data; start of gap buffer
        ....            Gap buffer (grows toward TPATOP)
        TPATOP          Top of TPA (read from CP/M page zero at 0006H)
        TPATOP+         BDOS, BIOS (not available to SEDIT)

    5.2  L80 Segment Layout

    L80 lays out memory in link order.  For each module, it places
    the module's DSEG first, then CSEG:

        [SEDIT DSEG][SEDIT CSEG]
        [SESCREEN DSEG][SESCREEN CSEG]
        [SEKEY DSEG][SEKEY CSEG]
        ...
        [SEHELP DSEG][SEHELP CSEG]

    L80 generates a 3-byte JMP instruction at 0100H that jumps past
    the first module's DSEG to reach the CSEG entry point.

    5.3  BMDATEND and Link Order

    BMDATEND is defined as EQU $ (current address) at the end of
    SEHELP.MAC's CSEG section, after all help strings and pointer
    tables.  Because SEHELP is linked last, BMDATEND captures the
    true end of all code and data across all modules.

    SEDIT.MAC reads BMDATEND at startup to calculate available
    buffer space:

        Buffer size = TPATOP - BMDATEND

    If BMDATEND is wrong (e.g. because SEHELP is not linked last),
    the gap buffer will start inside code/data and overwrite it,
    causing crashes.

    BMDATEND MUST be in CSEG (not DSEG) because L80 places DSEG
    before CSEG for each module.  If it were in DSEG, it would miss
    the module's own CSEG content.

    5.4  Gap Buffer

    The gap buffer occupies all memory from BMDATEND to TPATOP:

        [Text before cursor (R1)] [---GAP---] [Text after cursor (R2)]
        BMDATEND                  GAPBG GAPEN                   TPATOP

    Insertion writes at GAPBG and advances it.  Deletion adjusts
    gap boundaries.  Cursor movement copies bytes across the gap.
    This gives O(1) insert/delete at the cursor position.

    Line delimiter in the buffer is LF (0AH).  Files are stored on
    disk as CR+LF; the CR is inserted on save and stripped on load.

    5.5  Buffer Descriptor

    A 34-byte structure (BDESC0 in SEDIT.MAC DSEG) holds all state
    for the current buffer.  CURBDP points to it.  Fields:

        Offset  Size  Name       Description
        0       2     BD_BSTAR   Buffer base address
        2       2     BD_BSIZE   Buffer capacity (bytes)
        4       2     BD_GAPBG   Gap start offset
        6       2     BD_GAPEN   Gap end offset
        8       2     BD_TXEND   Logical text length
        10      2     BD_TOPLN   Top visible line number
        12      1     BD_CSROW   Cursor screen row (0-based)
        13      1     BD_CSCOL   Cursor text column (0-based)
        14      2     BD_CSOFF   Cursor byte offset
        16      2     BD_MRKBG   Block mark start (FFFFH=unset)
        18      2     BD_MRKEN   Block mark end (FFFFH=unset)
        20      1     BD_MODIF   Modified flag
        21      1     BD_SYNMD   Syntax mode (0=none, 1=ASM)
        22      12    BD_FNAME   Filename (drive + 8-char name + 3-char ext)


    6.  MODULE REFERENCE

    6.1  SEDIT.MAC - Main Module

    Entry point: START (at 0100H via L80 JMP)

    Initialization sequence:
      1. Save incoming stack pointer
      2. Set stack to private STKTOP
      3. Read TPATOP from CP/M page zero (0006H)
      4. Calculate buffer size, check minimum (9 KB)
      5. Initialize gap buffer (GBINIT)
      6. Initialize key bindings (KBINIT)
      7. Initialize screen (SCRINIT)
      8. Initialize virtual I/O (VIINIT)
      9. Load file from command-line FCB if present (FIOPEN)
      10. Enter main loop (MAINLP)

    Main loop (MAINLP):
      1. Auto-scroll if cursor outside visible columns
      2. Check DIRTY flag -> full redraw (SCRDRAW)
      3. Check DRTLINE flag -> current line redraw (SCREDCL)
      4. Update info bar (INFOBAR)
      5. Position hardware cursor (CURPOS)
      6. Wait for key (GETKEY, blocking)
      7. Dispatch: KT_CHAR -> insert/overwrite character
                   KT_ACT  -> jump via ACTTBL[action * 2]
      8. Loop

    Key exports: INSMODE, DIRTY, DRTLINE, CURBDP, TPATOP, DOEXIT

    6.2  SESCREEN.MAC - Screen Rendering

    All terminal output goes through this module.  VT100 escape
    sequences are emitted as $-terminated strings via BDOS function
    9 (print string) or character-by-character via BDOS function 6
    (direct console I/O).

    Key functions:
      SCRINIT   Initialize terminal (hide cursor, clear, draw chrome)
      SCRDRAW   Full 20-line redraw with line number gutter
      SCREDCL   Redraw current line only (performance optimization)
      INFOBAR   Update row 1 with file statistics
      CURPOS    Position hardware cursor via ESC[row;colH
      STATMSG   Display message on row 24
      OUTSTR    Output $-terminated string
      OUTCHAR   Output single character

    6.3  SEKEY.MAC - Keyboard Input

    GETKEY reads one logical keystroke and classifies it:
      B = KT_NONE (0): no key available
      B = KT_ACT  (1): C = action code (1-31)
      B = KT_CHAR (2): C = printable ASCII character

    Escape sequence decoding handles:
      CSI sequences (ESC [ ...): arrow keys, Home, End, PgUp, PgDn,
                                 Insert, Delete
      SS3 sequences (ESC O ...): F1-F4
      Bare ESC (no following sequence within timeout): menu action

    Two-key prefix sequences:
      Ctrl-K followed by a letter -> block/file operations
      Ctrl-Q followed by a letter -> navigation/find operations

    6.4  SEGAPBUF.MAC - Gap Buffer Engine

    Core text storage and manipulation.  All buffer operations work
    through the buffer descriptor pointed to by CURBDP.

    Key exports:
      GBINIT    Initialize buffer (set gap = entire buffer)
      GBINSRT   Insert byte at cursor (returns FFH if full)
      GBDLFT    Delete left (backspace); auto-absorbs CR before LF
      GBDELRT   Delete right
      GBMVUP/DN/LT/RT  Cursor movement (copy bytes across gap)
      GBPGUP/DN Page up/down (move by EDITROW lines)
      GBMLNS/E  Move to line start/end
      GBMVTOP   Move to file top
      GBMVEND   Move to file end
      GBDLLN    Delete entire current line
      GBWRDPV/NX  Word left/right
      GBGETLN   Get current line text into LINEBUF
      GBCNTLN   Count total lines in buffer
      GBCURLN   Find start of current line (O(line_length))
      GBFNDCS   Find cursor screen position
      GBRDLNO   Read line number at offset

    6.5  SEFILEIO.MAC - File I/O

    Uses CP/M FCB-based file operations (BDOS functions 15-26).

    FIOPEN: Opens and loads a file into the gap buffer.  If the file
    is too large, triggers FIOVFL which switches to virtual buffer
    mode and writes remaining data to the AFTER temp file.

    FISAVE: Saves buffer to disk.  In virtual mode, delegates to
    VISAVALL (three-phase save).  In normal mode, writes directly.
    Always creates a .BAK backup of the original file first.

    6.6  SEVIRTIO.MAC - Virtual Buffer I/O

    Manages disk-backed temp files for files larger than TPA.

    Three-region model:
      BEFORE temp (SEDIT00B.TMP) - lines above the buffer
      Gap buffer in TPA           - currently editable portion
      AFTER temp  (SEDIT00A.TMP) - lines below the buffer

    VIGOTO: Merge-split operation for crossing buffer boundaries.
      Phase 0: Write all three regions to MERGE temp
      Phase 1: Re-read MERGE, split at target line
      Phase 2: Cleanup, position cursor

    VISAVALL: Three-phase save for virtual mode.
      Phase 1: Copy BEFORE temp to output file
      Phase 2: Write gap buffer contents to output file
      Phase 3: Copy AFTER temp to output file
      Then flush, close, and delete temp files.

    6.7  SESYNTAX.MAC - Syntax Highlighting

    Per-line tokenizer for 8080/Z80 assembly.  SYNLINE walks one
    display line and builds a span table (SNTBL) of up to 16
    attribute regions.  SESCREEN consults this table during
    rendering to select SGR attributes.

    Token classification:
      Labels at column 1    -> ATTR_YEL
      Opcodes/directives    -> ATTR_GRN (matched against tables)
      Registers             -> ATTR_CYN (matched against REGTBL)
      Numbers               -> ATTR_MAG
      Strings               -> ATTR_MAG
      Comments (after ;)    -> ATTR_DIM
      Other text            -> ATTR_NRM

    SYNINIT detects file extension (.MAC, .ASM, .INC -> SYN_ASM;
    anything else -> SYN_NONE) and sets BD_SYNMD.

    6.8  SEHELP.MAC - Help Screen and BMDATEND

    HLPSHOW displays a two-column key reference overlay using
    pointer tables (HLPLTBL, HLPRTBL) for the left and right
    column text.  Waits for any keypress, then returns.

    Contains BMDATEND EQU $ at the end of CSEG - the critical
    end-of-code marker.  See section 5.3.

    6.9  Other Modules

    SEMENU.MAC:    ESC menu overlay with 9 options and handlers.
    SESEARCH.MAC:  Case-insensitive forward search through the gap
                   buffer.  Handles gap crossing transparently.
    SEBLOCK.MAC:   Block mark, copy (to CLIPBUF), delete, paste.
    SEKEYBND.MAC:  Reads SEDIT.KEY at startup to customize Ctrl-key
                   bindings.  Falls back to compiled-in defaults.


    7.  ADAPTING FOR DIFFERENT TERMINALS

    7.1  Escape Sequences (Output)

    All terminal escape sequences are defined as $-terminated string
    constants in SESCREEN.MAC DSEG:

        ESCSTR  ESC [           CSI introducer
        HOMSTR  ESC [ H         Cursor home
        CLRSTR  ESC [ 2 J       Clear screen
        CLREOL  ESC [ K         Erase to end of line
        HIDCUR  ESC [ ? 25 l    Hide cursor
        SHWCUR  ESC [ ? 25 h    Show cursor
        SGRRES  ESC [ 0 m       Reset attributes
        SGRBLD  ESC [ 1 m       Bold
        SGRDIM  ESC [ 2 m       Dim
        SGRREV  ESC [ 7 m       Reverse video

    Color strings (conditional on COLOR+SYNHI):
        SGRMAG  ESC [ 3 5 m     Magenta foreground
        SGRGRN  ESC [ 3 2 m     Green foreground
        SGRBLU  ESC [ 9 4 m     Bright blue foreground
        SGRRED  ESC [ 3 1 m     Red foreground
        SGRYEL  ESC [ 3 3 m     Yellow foreground
        SGRCYN  ESC [ 3 6 m     Cyan foreground
        SGRWHT  ESC [ 0 ; 3 7 m Reset + white

    To adapt for a non-VT100 terminal, replace these string constants
    with the equivalent sequences for your terminal.  The strings are
    all in the DSEG section of SESCREEN.MAC and are easy to locate.

    Cursor positioning (CURGOTO) builds the sequence ESC[row;colH
    dynamically.  For terminals that use a different cursor
    addressing scheme, modify the CURGOTO routine.

    Column mode toggle sequences are in SEMENU.MAC:
        DCWIDE  ESC [ ? 3 h     Set 132 columns (DECCOLM)
        DCNORM  ESC [ ? 3 l     Set 80 columns (DECCOLM)

    If your terminal does not support column mode switching, the
    80/132 toggle menu option can be left as-is (it will simply
    have no effect) or the menu handler can be modified.

    7.2  Escape Sequences (Input)

    Key input decoding is in SEKEY.MAC.  The escape sequence tables
    are:

    CSITBL: CSI (ESC [) sequences
      Maps final byte -> action code.  Entries for A-F (arrows,
      Home, End) and tilde sequences (1~..6~ for Home, Ins, Del,
      End, PgUp, PgDn).

    SS3TBL: SS3 (ESC O) sequences
      Maps P/Q/R/S -> F1/F2/F3/F4 actions.

    To add keys for a different terminal, add entries to these
    tables following the existing pattern.  Each entry is a byte
    pair: (character, action_code).  Tables are terminated by a
    zero byte.

    7.3  Screen Dimensions

    Screen size constants are in SEDIT.INC:

        SCRROWS  EQU  24       Terminal rows
        SCRCOLS  EQU  80       Terminal columns
        EDITROW  EQU  20       Number of edit area rows
        EDITFR   EQU  3        First edit row (1-based)
        SEPRROW  EQU  23       Separator row
        STATROW  EQU  24       Status line row

    To adapt for a different screen size (e.g. 25 rows), adjust
    these constants.  EDITROW controls how many text lines are
    displayed; increase it by the number of added rows.

    Note: EDITROW affects the size of several arrays (e.g. the
    CMLST comment state array in SESCREEN.MAC when syntax
    highlighting is enabled).  Search for EDITROW references
    when changing this value.

    7.4  Monochrome Terminals

    Set COLOR EQU 0 in SEDIT.INC (and in the inlined copies in
    SESCREEN.MAC and SESYNTAX.MAC).  This eliminates all SGR color
    sequences.  Bold, dim, and reverse video are still used for
    the info bar, ruler, and separator.

    For terminals that do not support even bold/dim/reverse, replace
    the SGR strings with empty sequences (just "$" terminators).

    7.5  Single-Byte Key Codes

    SEKEY.MAC includes a table (SBYTBL) for terminals that send
    single high-byte codes (>= 80H) for special keys instead of
    escape sequences:

        0EDH -> Cursor up       0ECH -> Cursor down
        0EBH -> Cursor left     0EAH -> Cursor right
        0EFH -> Page up         0EEH -> Page down
        0F3H -> Insert toggle   0F2H -> Delete right
        0F1H -> Home            0F0H -> End

    Modify this table for terminals with different high-byte key
    encodings.


    8.  CODING CONVENTIONS

    8.1  Register Usage

    BDOS calls (CALL 0005H) clobber ALL registers.  Any value
    needed after a BDOS call must be saved to memory (STA) or
    the stack (PUSH) beforehand.

    Gap buffer accessor functions (GBBASE, GBBSIZ, GBGAPEN, etc.)
    clobber register A.  Save A before calling if needed.

    GBBASE and GBBSIZ return results in DE and clobber A and HL.
    All other accessors return results in HL.

    8.2  Buffer Descriptor Access Pattern

        LHLD    CURBDP          ; HL = descriptor base
        MVI     A,BD_field      ; A = field offset
        ADD     L
        MOV     L,A
        MVI     A,0
        ADC     H
        MOV     H,A             ; HL -> field
        MOV     E,M             ; read low byte
        INX     H
        MOV     D,M             ; read high byte (for word fields)

    8.3  Dirty Flag Protocol

        MVI     A,1
        STA     DIRTY           ; request full screen redraw
        ; or
        STA     DRTLINE         ; request current line redraw only

    The main loop checks DIRTY first (full redraw), then DRTLINE
    (line redraw), then does nothing (cursor-only update).

    8.4  No Z80 Instructions

    SEDIT must run on an Intel 8080.  Do not use any Z80-only
    instructions including but not limited to: EX, DJNZ, JR,
    LDIR, IX, IY, or alternate register sets.

    8.5  SEDIT.INC Inlining Caveat

    CPMFMT.PY expands INCLUDE SEDIT.INC on the first run only.
    After that, the INCLUDE directive is replaced by inlined content.
    Subsequent runs of CPMFMT.PY only normalize line endings.

    If SEDIT.INC is edited, the inlined copies in .MAC files are
    NOT automatically updated.  You must either:
      - Restore the INCLUDE directive in each affected .MAC file
        and re-run CPMFMT.PY, or
      - Manually update the inlined EQUs in each .MAC file

    In practice, the constants that differ between modules are
    COLOR and SYNHI (only used by SESCREEN.MAC and SESYNTAX.MAC).
    Most other constants are used by all modules identically.


    9.  BUILD TROUBLESHOOTING

    9.1  Unresolved External

    If L80 reports an unresolved external symbol, check:
      - The symbol is declared PUBLIC in the providing module
      - The symbol is declared EXTRN in the consuming module
      - The providing module is included in the L80 link command
      - The symbol spelling matches exactly (M80 is case-insensitive
        but L80 may preserve case in error messages)

    9.2  Assembly Errors After Editing

    If M80 reports errors after editing a .MAC file:
      - Run python CPMFMT.PY on the file first
      - Check that the Ctrl-Z EOF marker is present (CPMFMT.PY
        adds it automatically)
      - Check that line endings are CR+LF

    9.3  BMDATEND Wrong / Buffer Overwrites Code

    If the editor crashes or displays corrupted help text:
      - Verify SEHELP is the last module in the L80 link command
      - Verify BMDATEND EQU $ is in CSEG (not DSEG) in SEHELP.MAC
      - Verify no other module defines code or data after SEHELP

    9.4  DSEG Variable Placement

    M80 may fail to resolve labels defined after large DS or DW
    blocks in DSEG.  Define labels near the top of each module's
    DSEG section, before large tables or buffers.


    10. REVISION HISTORY

    v1.10   Virtual buffer mode for files larger than TPA.
            SEVIRTIO.MAC module added.  FIOVFL overflow handler in
            SEFILEIO.MAC.  Three-phase save (VISAVALL).  VIGOTO
            merge-split for cross-boundary navigation.
    v1.09   Exit on file-too-large error at startup.
    v1.08   80/132 column toggle.  GBCURLN and SCREDCL bug fixes.
    v1.03   Multiple bug fixes: backspace CR orphan, filename/drive
            display, string highlight ordering, GBMVLT register
            clobber, BMDATEND DSEG/CSEG placement.
    v1.02   TPATOP address fix (0006H).  SCREDCL performance fix
            (O(line_length) via GBCURLN instead of O(line_number)).
    v1.0    Initial release.


